President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate three individuals for judicial positions. 

1. Halil "Sul" Ozerden of Mississippi is nominated to serve as a Circuit Judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit. Ozerden currently serves as a U.S. District Judge for the Southern District of Mississippi. He has previous experience as a partner at a law firm and as a law clerk to a judge in the U.S. District Court. Ozerden is a former flight officer in the United States Navy and holds a B.S. from Georgetown University and a J.D. from Stanford Law School.

2. John F. Kness of Illinois is nominated to serve as a Judge on the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois. Kness is currently the General Counsel of the College of DuPage and has previous experience as an Assistant U.S. Attorney. He also served as a law clerk to a judge in the U.S. Court of Appeals. Kness holds a B.A. and J.D. from Northwestern University.

3. Eleni M. Roumel of Virginia is nominated to serve as a Judge on the U.S. Court of Federal Claims. Roumel currently serves as Deputy Counsel to the Vice President of the United States and previously worked as Assistant General Counsel to the United States House of Representatives. She also has experience as a partner at a law firm and as an adjunct professor. Roumel holds a B.A. from Wake Forest University, an M.B.A. from Tulane University, and a J.D. from Tulane Law School.